<h1 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h1>

<p>It still seems quite interesting to generalize Cheonâ€™s construction (with the
goal of â€œpolynomial approximation using <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mo>+</mo><mo separator="true">,</mo><mo>Ã—</mo><mo separator="true">,</mo><mo>âˆ˜</mo><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\{+,\times,\circ\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mopen">{</span><span class="mord">+</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">Ã—</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">âˆ˜</span><span class="mclose">}</span></span></span></span>â€), but approaches
which try to view their construction as a Bernstein-type construction seem to
run into (many) issues.</p>

<ol>
  <li>The computations just donâ€™t work out (although this could maybe be fixed with
some additional work)</li>
  <li>The polynomial approximation scheme does not seem to show up in the
literature, so one would have to develop it generically before trying to
apply it to FHE</li>
  <li>â€œConvexity issuesâ€</li>
</ol>

<p>This last part deserves elaborating.
Recall that Cheon et alâ€™s idea was to find some fixed â€œbaseâ€ polynomial, and
then <em>compose</em> it.
This is why they cared about increasing convexity (so in each â€œiterationâ€,
points get â€œpushedâ€ in the right way).
It is not clear how a suitably-developed Bernstein-type approximation scheme
could be used for such a purpose.
You would at least need not only polynomial approximation of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">f(x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault" style="margin-right:0.10764em;">f</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathdefault">x</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span>, but also
of its derivatives.
One could try to look for polynomial approximation of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">f(x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault" style="margin-right:0.10764em;">f</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathdefault">x</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> in the
<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">C^2[0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1.064108em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathdefault" style="margin-right:0.07153em;">C</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height:0.8141079999999999em;"><span style="top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height:2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mopen">[</span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mclose">]</span></span></span></span> norm:</p>

